    <fr:title text="Points of the dissolution locale">Points of the dissolution locale</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Classically, for every locale <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:link href="misc-000E.xml" title="Dissolution locale" addr="misc-000E" type="local">dissolution locale</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_d]]></fr:tex> has the same points as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="trebor.xml" title="Trebor" addr="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:source-path>/Users/trebor/Desktop/blog/forest/trees/misc-000G.tree</fr:source-path><fr:anchor>599</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/429</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-429.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>We want to prove the canonical map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (1, X_d) \to  \hom (1, X)]]></fr:tex> is a bijection. All the sublocales of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> are closed since there are only two of them. Therefore for every map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \to  X]]></fr:tex>, the preimage of every sublocale is trivially closed, and therefore it factors through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_d \to  X]]></fr:tex> uniquely. This implies the desired bijection.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
